DMO may use $2.8 Eurobond to redeem local debts The declining value of transactions at the Investors and Exporters Window (I&E Window), which recorded $1.98 billion in November, is a cause for renewed concerns, especially as uncertainty has hit the price of crude oil at the international market.
 
The amount, which is the the lowest figure recorded since August 2017, is an indication of foreign investors’ cautious approach to investing in Nigeria, even as capital flow reversal thrive on politically tensed environment.
 
The Head of Research at FSDH Merchant Bank Limited, Ayodele Akinwunmi, during the lender’s monthly economic outlook, said the development is worrisome, especially now that Nigeria’s major foreign exchange earner is going through volatility.Citing the data obtained from the FMDQ OTC Securities Exchange on the total capital importation through the segment, he noted that CBN remained the largest contributors to the inflow in November, a trend observed in the last three months.  To enable commenting and other interactive features, please switch to the more advanced .